{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5763ff31-fbff-4b2a-a2e5-baacef3d242a","content":"You can download `dotnet-trace` as a **standalone binary** — no SDK needed.\n\n**Inside the container, run:**\n\n```bash\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o /tmp/dotnet-trace\nchmod +x /tmp/dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**Then collect a CPU trace:**\n\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n/tmp/dotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect with the cpu-sampling profile (good for high-CPU)\n/tmp/dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling -o /tmp/trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Key notes:**\n\n- Use `linux-arm64` instead of `linux-x64` if you're on ARM.\n- The resulting `.nettrace` file can be analyzed in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or converted to speedscope format with `--format speedscope`.\n- To copy the trace out: `docker cp <container>:/tmp/trace.nettrace .`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"918096e6-5635-492e-926c-501f6be2a545","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU.\n\nThis is a knowledge question about .NET diagnostics tooling. I can answer this directly from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase.\n\nKey points:\n1. `dotnet-trace` is a .NET global tool, but you can also get it as a standalone download (no SDK required).\n2. For containers without the SDK, you can download the standalone version directly.\n\nLet me provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":401,"requestId":"D7EE:11233D:E9E129:10C9A69:69F2B049"},"id":"c0d1790e-03b1-4051-9eff-d75601dcd17d","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:28:50.471Z","parentId":"3aa1b0b5-168d-4f3a-898a-c36e72c5e8fd"}
